---
import Layout from "../layouts/Main.astro";
import Hornet from "../assets/4cb87f_8a4df804fa0e4288b85a020fafe814dd~mv2.avif";
---

<Layout title="Asian Hornet - Dover & District Beekeepers' Association">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <!-- Page Header -->
    <div class="mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-amber-900 mb-4">
        Yellow-Legged Hornet
      </h1>
      <p class="text-2xl text-gray-600 mb-6">(also known as Asian Hornet)</p>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        Asian Hornets are a threat to all pollinators, not just bees. With our
        proximity to the Channel, DDBKA members have been working hard over the
        last couple of years to set out traps and raise awareness to the public
        in our area.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Asian Hornet Image -->
    <div class="mb-12">
      <a
        href="https://risc.brc.ac.uk/alert.php?species=asian_hornet"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="block hover:opacity-95 transition-opacity"
      >
        <img
          src={Hornet.src}
          alt="Asian Hornet (Vespa velutina) showing distinctive yellow legs and black body with orange band - slightly smaller and darker than our native European hornet."
          class="w-full rounded-xl shadow-lg"
        />
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Information Sections -->
    <div class="space-y-12 mb-12">
      <!-- Identification Section -->
      <section class="bg-white p-8 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber-900 mb-4">Identification</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The Asian Hornet (Vespa velutina) is smaller than our native European
          hornet. Key identifying features include:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Predominantly black body with a distinctive yellow or orange band
              on the fourth abdominal segment</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Yellow legs (hence "yellow-legged")</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Dark thorax with a velvety appearance</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700">Orange face (from the front view)</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Why It Matters -->
      <section class="bg-white p-8 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber-900 mb-4">
          Why Asian Hornets Are a Threat
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Asian Hornets pose a significant threat to:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              ><strong>Honey bees:</strong> They hunt bees to feed their larvae,
              often hovering outside hives to catch returning foragers</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              ><strong>Other pollinators:</strong> They also prey on other beneficial
              insects including native wasps and hoverflies</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              ><strong>Biodiversity:</strong> Their presence can disrupt local ecosystems
              and reduce pollination</span
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Our Efforts -->
      <section class="bg-white p-8 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber-900 mb-4">DDBKA's Response</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Due to our proximity to the English Channel, Dover and District is on
          the front line of Asian Hornet monitoring. Our members are actively:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Setting out monitoring traps throughout the area</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Raising public awareness about identification and reporting</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Working with local authorities and the National Bee Unit</span
            >
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start">
            <span class="text-amber-600 mr-3">•</span>
            <span class="text-gray-700"
              >Training members in Asian Hornet identification and response
              protocols</span
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Resources -->
      <section
        class="bg-amber-50 p-8 rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-amber-100"
      >
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber-900 mb-4">
          Further Information
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          For detailed information about Asian Hornet identification, reporting
          procedures, and the latest updates, please visit:
        </p>
        <a
          href="https://www.bbka.org.uk/asian-yellow-legged-hornet"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="inline-block px-8 py-3 bg-amber-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg shadow-md hover:bg-amber-700 transition-colors mb-6"
        >
          BBKA Asian Hornet Information
        </a>
        <p class="text-gray-600">
          If you have questions or concerns, please contact our Asian Hornet
          Co-ordinator, Jackie Thomas, via: <a
            href="mailto:doveranddistrictbeekeepers@gmail.com"
            class="text-amber-600 font-semibold hover:underline"
            >doveranddistrictbeekeepers@gmail.com</a
          >
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- Alert Section -->
    <div
      class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-8 rounded-lg shadow-sm mb-12"
    >
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-red-900 mb-4">
        ⚠️ Spotted an Asian Hornet?
      </h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        If you think you have seen an Asian Hornet, it's crucial to report it
        immediately. Early detection and rapid response are essential to protect
        our pollinators.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4">
        <a
          href="https://risc.brc.ac.uk/alert.php?species=asian_hornet"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="inline-block px-8 py-3 bg-red-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg shadow-md hover:bg-red-700 transition-colors text-center"
        >
          Report a Sighting
        </a>
        <a
          href="/contact"
          class="inline-block px-8 py-3 bg-white text-red-900 border-2 border-red-900 font-semibold rounded-lg shadow-sm hover:bg-red-50 transition-colors text-center"
        >
          Contact DDBKA
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
